<TITLE> Govt interfering with judiciary: BNP </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 15 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh Nationalist Party, the main opposition, has accused the government of 'interfering with' the judiciary. "We have noted with regret that the government law officers including the attorney general have been passing remarks and giving such indications as should hinder the dispensation of justice," secretary-general Khandaker Delwar Hossain said. "This certainly is not going to help promoting democratic practices and an independent judiciary," he said on Sunday at a discussion organised by Banglar Alo photo and news agency marking its first anniversary at National Press Club. Delwar said, "The fourth pillar of the state is the newspaper, whose upright pen should keep the people aware of the needs of fortifying our independence through upholding democratic practices." "The newspapers must continue to work to render people aware of what is happening around us." He criticised the role of some newspapers. Mentioning that the country is passing a very 'crucial' period of time, the BNP leader said, "Democracy will be at stake unless the rule of law, an independent judiciary and a streamlined administration are not in place." "The present government is hindering with justice dispensation through unwarranted interference, which may jeopardise democratic processes, unless thwarted." The attorney general and other law officers are busy influencing the law courts through passing indicative comments, he alleged. Abdul Latif Nizami of Islami Oikyo Jote, news agency adviser Anisul Haq, among others, also spoke. b
